"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/45b711d0-d12b-4ed4-89ff-24783c6b1fa4.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 18:03:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/white-house-says-amazon-google-meta-microsoft-agree-to-ai-safeguards-eabe3680</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/white-house-says-amazon-google-meta-microsoft-agree-to-ai-safeguards-eabe3680<author><![CDATA[Sabrina SiddiquiDeepa Seetharaman]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>软件</category><category>应用软件</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>建筑施工</category><category>住宅建筑施工</category><category>零售批发</category><category>伊泰林</category><category>市场研究/公共关系</category><category>公共关系</category><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>广告/营销/公共关系</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>计算</category><category>建造</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>电子商务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>零售</category><category>技术</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>慈善/志愿服务</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>亚马逊网站</category><category>亚马逊</category><category>谷歌</category><category>谷歌</category><category>微软</category><category>微软公司</category><category>元平台</category><category>梅塔</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>慈善机构</category><category>志愿服务</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>电脑</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>软件</category><category>应用软件</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>建筑施工</category><category>住宅建筑施工</category><category>零售</category><category>批发的</category><category>电子邮寄</category><category>市场调查</category><category>公共关系</category><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>广告</category><category>营销</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>计算</category><category>建造</category><category>房地产</category><category>电子商务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Could Gadgets Make Your Pet Love You More?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>大量新设备有望让您的西班牙猎犬或暹罗犬安全、快乐并与您相爱，同时让您的生活更轻松。但并非所有动物都能获得兽医的认可。 <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820976/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="PAWS AND CLAWS While there aren’t&nbsp;pet-specific&nbsp;cell phones and VR headsets (yet), plenty of dogs and cats are now living with gadgets like automatic litter boxes and ball launchers. Not all of this&nbsp;tech&nbsp;is helping." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> PAWS AND CLAWS While there aren&#39;t pet-specific cell phones and VR headsets (yet), plenty of dogs and cats are now living with gadgets like automatic litter boxes and ball launchers. Not all of this tech is helping. Lauren Carney; Shayan Asgharnia (2) <span>Lauren Carney; Shayan Asgharnia (2)</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001036311"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001036311"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Sophia Benoit</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 21, 2023 2:00 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/could-gadgets-make-your-pet-love-you-more-we-found-6-that-mightand-3-that-wont-e074af0e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p class="has-drop-cap"> <strong>ACCORDING TO</strong> her Twitter bio, Sharkboots “Boots” Shadynasty, nine years old, is “allergic to chicken and has behavioral issues.” One of those issues is her propensity for peeing in beds. Her “mom,” Leisha Riddel, 34, an art director in Toronto, says she tried everything to persuade the cat to relieve herself in the litter box instead: changing litter thrice daily, using a motion-activated spray (named “ <a href="https://store.petsafe.net/ssscat-spray-pet-deterrent" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">SSSCAT</a> ”) meant to deter pets from certain areas of your home, even having three separate litter boxes so that Boots could rotate.</p><p> The only thing that curbed Boots&#39;s poor pee patterns? The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/automatic-litter-boxes-do-they-freak-cats-out-d815a065?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Litter-Robot 4</a> , a $699 spherical litter “box” that rotates slowly, sifting out the clean litter and dropping any clumps into an easily emptied drawer. The Wi-Fi-enabled device not only cleans itself after each use—hence its promise to eliminate odors—it tracks when each of your cats have used it. You can even purchase <a href="https://www.litter-robot.com/litter-robot/accessories/litter-robot-4-camera-mount-kit.html" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">a camera attachment</a> to watch your cat do its business. Riddel bought her luxury litter box second hand, and insists that, while the price caused some pain, the box is worth it.</p><p> A kitty pee cam might seem like overkill, but I get it. I come from a long line of pet-obsessed suckers. In an oft-told story, my grandmother attempted to dissuade Puma, the family cat, from jumping on the kitchen counter by offering him pieces of whatever meat my grandfather, a butcher, brought home. (You might understand that this only encouraged Puma). My aunt cooks full human meals for her beagles. My sister and brother-in-law let their Great Dane sleep beside them in an overpopulated queen-sized bed. In short, no one in my family has the heart to tell an animal “no.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="695" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821705?width=700&amp;height=695" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> RAISING MISS DAISY There is little most pet owners wouldn&#39;t do to extend the life of their furry friends, be that investing in automatic litter boxes or shelling out for more expensive food.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Illustration: Lauren Carney; Shayan Asgharnia</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Innovations in litter box design, monitoring cameras and pet trackers have only further enabled my clan to go overboard in the name of giving our animals better lives. Which is how, after a couple of glasses of wine, I found myself ordering a DNA test for my rescue dog, Party. When the results came back, they included a photo of a dog who is presumably her mom (they share 49% of their DNA and both sit in arm chairs the same way). I also found out that Party was marked “clear for 29 genetic conditions that could impact her early vet visits.” Should I ever want to, I can pay and upgrade to find out more about her health.</p><p> It&#39;s hard to resist products, even pricey ones, that promise to make our pets happier or healthier. Indeed, a <a href="https://www.skyquestt.com/sample-request/pet-tech-market" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">2022 study</a> by Skyquest Technology Consulting reports that “83% of pet owners in North America and Europe own at least one pet tech device.” Among the factors driving this: <a href="https://www.avma.org/news/pet-ownership-rate-stabilizes-spending-increases" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">increases in pet ownership</a> over the past few years (“ <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pandemic-puppies-return-reopened-offices-11621265190?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">pandemic puppies</a> ” was a real phenomenon);  a <a href="https://globalpetindustry.com/article/pet-wearables-booming-industry-set-grow-even-further" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">growing desire to monitor pet health</a> ; and the way <a href="https://www.fortunebusinessinsights.com/pet-tech-market-105924" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">new technologies</a> , especially <a href="https://globalpetindustry.com/article/newest-trends-ai-pet-tech" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">AI-based ones</a> , are fueling innovation.</p><h3> The Benefits of Sequencing Your Samoyed&#39;s Genome</h3><p> I asked St. Louis-based veterinarian Dr. Emily Goyda about DNA tests, and while she said she has used information from the results, she cautioned, “Some of those markers are clinically relevant, but I wouldn&#39;t put a huge stake in an over-the-counter test.” Which is fair, but the test did mostly show dog relatives from Bakersfield, Calif., a city three hours away from where Party was found.</p><p> I&#39;m not a “reach out and try to meet up with my dog&#39;s half siblings” kind of person—but I understand such information&#39;s allure. DNA tests like Embark for dogs and Basepaws for cats, which promise to yield data relevant to the pet&#39;s health, are skyrocketing in popularity.</p><p> Both companies also offer tests that let you assess your dog&#39;s gut health and your cat&#39;s oral hygiene. (Assume it&#39;s bad. They eat bugs.) Armed with a mountain of data, some pet owners are getting a little wound up.</p><h3> The Downside of DNA Testing</h3><p> Dr. William Adams, a veterinarian who practices on Long Island, NY, says that owners often come in worried about results he doesn&#39;t find concerning, such as an ancestry-based risk of kidney stones. “Knowing your pet is predisposed to things can have value, but it can also be abused. Every time your dog looks at you funny, are you going to freak out instead of just enjoying your time with your pet?” Both he and Goyda  say that knowing about medication sensitivities, which Embark offers, can help them in their practice, but neither think DNA testing is necessary.</p><p> Companies understand, though, that pet owners will pay for the promise of health and safety. GPS-enabled collars let you find your pet if it runs off, and the <a href="https://www.whistle.com/products/whistle-health-gps-dog-tracker-activity-monitor" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">Whistle Go Explore 2.0 Smart Tracker</a> , for one, also tracks licking and itching, which can indicate a reaction or an allergy. The <a href="https://furbo.com/us/products/furbo-dog-nanny" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">Furbo Nanny</a> , a subscription upgrade to a standard Furbo pet camera can alert you if a person is in your home while you&#39;re away, if your dog is barking, or if there&#39;s a smoke or carbon monoxide alarm going off.</p><h3> Who Are These Gadgets Actually For?</h3><p> Another large chunk of pet-tech gadgets comprises items that make your life as a pet owner easier. Who wants to scoop litter or throw the ball 947 times? Automatic pet feeders got the thumbs-up from veterinarians we spoke to, especially for cats—who prefer lots of little meals throughout the day. Programming an automatic feeder to feed your cat at night might prevent that dreaded 5 am wake-up call. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818780?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An automatic ball thrower? I already have one—namely you.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: The Farmers Dog</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> But sometimes the shortcut falls short. Plenty of gadgets promise to help your dog get  exercise while you mostly laze about. These can work for some pets, but not all.</p><p> Dog treadmills, for example, could help dogs who get easily distracted and overreact to stimuli on walks but who still need lots of exercise. That said, treadmills can&#39;t replace mentally stimulating activities your dog needs, like sniffing, digging or chasing. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="wsj-article-pullquote article__inset__pullquote "><p class="pullquote-content article__inset__pullquote__quote"> <span class="l-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--left">“</span> Innovations in litter-box design, monitoring cameras and pet trackers have only further enabled us to go overboard. <span class="r-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--right">”</span></p></div></div><p> “Consult with your veterinarian to see how much activity is appropriate for your dog specifically, because you can overdo it,” said Dr. Heather Fraser, a New Orleans vet. Not every dog wants to run 4 miles, treadmill notwithstanding.</p><p> Vets issued similar warnings for automatic ball launchers, designed to play fetch with your dog without ever getting tired. Adams cautions that an endless round of fetch can make dogs obsessed, which can inhibit them socially. Games like fetch are great because they give dogs opportunities to spend time with you, and let you stimulate their minds. When you outsource that work to a machine that doesn&#39;t ever stop, behavioral issues like fixation can emerge.</p><h3> Here&#39;s the Bottom Line</h3><p> Every expert we spoke to agreed that while any tech might work for some pets, the most important thing when purchasing gear is to know your pet. For example, grooming vacuums, which use suction to help brush a dog, often get great reviews, but knowing my dog Party&#39;s relationship with the vacuum-vacuum, I doubt she&#39;d welcome a pet-vacuum with open paws.</p><p> Your basset hound doesn&#39;t need a treadmill, and if your cat freaks out every time you turn on your electric toothbrush, you could soon find yourself selling a fancy litter box at a massive loss on Facebook Marketplace.</p><p> If you don&#39;t know what is best for your pet, ask your vet to help you pinpoint what might or might not work. Most are more than happy to guide you through even the silliest questions.</p><p> I know because I&#39;ve now asked all of them. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> FETCH THESE, SCRATCH THOSE</h3><p> <em>Not all pet gear is created equal. Here&#39;s how the vets and other experts we spoke with rated nine accessories.</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> Gear for Dogs </h3><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819465?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div><h4>推荐</h4><p>Sylvia Wes, certified professional dog trainer, has tested multiple tracking collars, and calls the Whistle Go Explore 2.0 Smart Tracker her “favorite thing.” The collar not only actually uses LTE and GPS to track pets, but also keeps notes on their sleep and behaviors like itching and licking that you might want to bring up with a vet. <em>$129, <a href="https://www.whistle.com/products/whistle-health-gps-dog-tracker-activity-monitor" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">Whistle.com</a></em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819461?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div><h4> It&#39;s Fine</h4><p> Vets and trainers say dog treadmills like the Dog Pacer 4.0, have uses, but only for certain dogs. Not all dogs want or need to run long distances, so ask your vet about your own dog&#39;s exercise needs. Also, as Dr. Emily Goyda pointed out, exercise isn&#39;t a substitute for mental stimulation for dogs with anxiety issues. <em>$799, <a href="https://dogpacer.com/product/dog-treadmill/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">DogPacer.com</a></em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819462?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div><h4> Skip It</h4><p> While ball launchers like iFetch Ball Launcher can help you avoid the monotony of ball throwing duties, Dr. William Adams warns that, with some dogs, you should limit your reliance on such tools. “There have been some recent studies that actually say that fetch is addictive to dogs and it can have a similar feedback loop as drugs for people.” <em>$230, <a href="https://goifetch.com/products/ifetch-too-ball-launcher-medium-to-large-dogs" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">GoIFetch.com</a></em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> Gear for Cats </h3><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819460?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div><h4>推荐</h4><p>If you&#39;re ready to splurge on your cat (and yourself), vets recommend the Litter-Robot 4. Not only is it a litter box that literally cleans itself, eliminating the smelliest fact of cat parenthood, it also collects data about your cat (or cats) to alert you, via its easy-to-use app, about any concerning bathroom habits, like constipation. <em>$699, <a href="https://www.litter-robot.com/litter-robot-4.html" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">Litter-Robot.com</a></em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819459?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div><h4> It&#39;s Fine</h4><p> Automatic feeders are certainly not a requirement, but vets say they&#39;re great for cats who like to eat multiple small meals throughout the day, sometimes at night. The Catit PIXI Smart 6-Meal Feeder can handle both dry food and wet food—thanks to room for ice packs that keep the food cool—which makes it work for any feline&#39;s diet. <em>$135, <a href="https://catit.us/products/catit-pixi-smart-6-meal-feeder" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">CatIt.us</a></em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="426" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818782?width=639&amp;height=426" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div><h4> Skip It</h4><p> SurePet&#39;s Microchip Cat Door uses your pet&#39;s existing microchip to easily allow your cat to go in and out of the house and prevents other critters from getting in. It works well, which could make it a boon for folks who constantly find their neighbor&#39;s bichon frisé in their den, but most vets don&#39;t recommend letting your cat outside. <em>$216, <a href="https://www.surepetcare.com/en-us/pet-doors/microchip-cat-flap-connect" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">SurePetCare.com</a></em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> Gear for Both </h3><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="426" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818791?width=639&amp;height=426" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Embark Vet</p></figcaption></figure></div><h4>推荐</h4><p>DNA kits like Embark for dogs and BasePaws for cats offer a ton of information. Getting one back can be fun, allowing you to identify potential relatives of your pet. Some things you&#39;ll learn won&#39;t be relevant, but vets say the results can help them see how a pet will respond to certain medications. <em>$199, <a href="https://embarkvet.com/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">EmbarkVet.com</a> ; $159, <a href="https://basepaws.com/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">Basepaws.com</a></em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819464?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div><h4> It&#39;s Fine</h4><p> The Furbo 360 Camera lets you stare at your pet all day, even when you&#39;re away. You can speak to pets through its speaker and even toss them treats, though Fraser warns that some pets might be frustrated by the loud treat-shooting mechanism or their inability to find you after hearing your voice. Otherwise, she considers the device harmless. <em>$210, <a href="https://furbo.com/us/products/furbo-360-dog-camera" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">Furbo.com</a></em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819468?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div><h4> Skip It</h4><p> If you&#39;ve ever wished that you could simply vacuum the dog instead of every single surface in your house, the furMe Grooming Vacuum Kit might appeal. But pets might not exactly love having a vacuum on them. If your pet has a chill attitude, vets say this could be OK. But be careful using attachments with blades. <em>$200, <a href="https://shopfurme.com/products/furme-original-professional-pet-grooming-vacuum-kit" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">ShopFurMe.com</a></em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> Should You Be Splurging on a Fancier Feast? </h3><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="610" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820014?width=639&amp;height=610" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> BETTER BITE? Nom Nom meals are like grain bowls.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: NomNom NOW</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The primary form of nutrition for most American pets is some form of kibble—usually a mixture of ground meat, grains and vegetables compressed into a pellet. In recent years, however, several companies have begun pushing the idea that what your dogs and cats eat should look more like what you&#39;d serve yourself, even if it costs more. These brands include <a href="https://www.thefarmersdog.com/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">the Farmer&#39;s Dog</a> and <a href="https://www.nomnomnow.com/" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">Nom Nom</a> , both of which ship out prepackaged meals with ingredients such as turkey chunks, carrot slices and, amazingly, lentils. Other pet owners have taken to cooking meals for their dogs and cats, or purchasing raw meat for a “raw food” diet in hopes of benefiting their pet.</p><p> Some of these trends concern some experts. “Research has shown that the majority of online homemade diet recipes are not balanced or complete,” said Dr. Monica Tarantino, a  vet in Charlotte, NC  She says vets can often help devise specific plans for pets with cancer, cognitive decline or heart disease, but most pets don&#39;t require the effort.</p><p> When choosing food, she and Dr. Kristi Chow, a vet in Indianapolis, say to check packaging to see whether the Association of American Feed Control Officials has verified the food. Commercial kibble from brands like Hill&#39;s, Iams and Purina usually has this distinction, as do many premade fresh food diets. But don&#39;t feel guilty if you&#39;re not springing for fresh grub. If the food&#39;s verified, what mainly matters is whether your pet will actually eat it.</p><p> <em>《华尔街日报》没有得到其文章中列出的作为产品销售渠道的零售商的补偿。上市零售商通常不是唯一的零售店。</em></p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What tools make your pet love you more?加入下面的对话。</em> </p></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> mORE IN GEAR &amp; GADGETS</h4><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/have-heirlooms-you-want-to-pass-down-make-your-kids-download-this-app-93248016?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Have Heirlooms You Want to Pass Down? Make Your Kids Download This App</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wait-are-hearing-aids-cool-now-ask-millennials-629e7e55?mod=article_relatedinline&amp;mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Wait, Are Hearing Aids Cool Now? Ask Millennials</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-baby-boomers-love-the-kindleand-millennials-dont-e28c1eae?mod=article_relatedinline&amp;mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Why Baby Boomers Love the Kindle—and Millennials Don&#39;t</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/outdoor-concert-guide-what-to-bring-8d7f7467?mod=article_relatedinline&amp;mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">The Ultimate Outdoor Concert Survival Kit: 7 Things You Should Never Leave at Home</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/automatic-coffee-makers-balmuda-the-brew-review-56a93d45?mod=article_relatedinline&amp;mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Pour-Over Coffee Is a Hassle. Can a $699 Machine Make Mornings Easier?</a></li></ul></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 18:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/could-gadgets-make-your-pet-love-you-more-we-found-6-that-mightand-3-that-wont-e074af0e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/could-gadgets-make-your-pet-love-you-more-we-found-6-that-mightand-3-that-wont-e074af0e<category>下班</category><category>新产品/服务</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>产品与服务</category><category>Animal Health</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>健康</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>新产品</category><category>服务</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>产品</category><category>animal health</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>健康</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Flying Wings, Rockets, Gliders: Air Force Envisions Its Next Cargo Workhorses]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Pentagon wants fleet able to fly vast distances in support of US forces in Pacific under policy to deter China <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818027/?width=3000&amp;size=1.689" alt="The U.S. Air Force C-5M Super Galaxy has been an anchor of the military cargo fleet for decades." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> The US Air Force C-5M Super Galaxy has been an anchor of the military cargo fleet for decades. US Air Force <span>US Air Force</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001063440"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001063440"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/doug-cameron" itemprop="url" rel="author">Doug Cameron</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 21, 2023 1:39 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/united-states-air-force-cargo-plane-development-china-1075021a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Sometimes, you need a really big plane.</p><p> An Air Force C-17 Globemaster <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/three-killed-in-kabul-airport-as-afghans-scramble-to-escape-taliban-11629096273?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">evacuated 640 passengers</a> in a single flight from Kabul during the US withdrawal two years ago. The C-5M Super Galaxy, even bigger than the Globemaster, can carry anything in the Army&#39;s arsenal—or the presidential motorcade and helicopter.</p><p> The mammoth jets, however, are aging and out of production. That has pushed the Pentagon to start looking at replacements capable of flying vast distances in support of US forces in the Pacific as part of its policy to deter China.  More broadly, the Air Force envisages a family of systems including a large new aircraft, small uncrewed delivery drones, gliders, and even space rockets to blast cargo anywhere in the world within minutes.</p><p> Air Force leaders are still sketching out requirements for the next generation of airlift planes. They are trying out ideas in an exercise this month across the Pacific called Mobility Guardian 2023 involving 70 cargo and refueling aircraft and 3,000 airmen and troops.</p><p> &#39;We&#39;ll really test ourselves on how quickly we can move,” Air Force Chief of Staff Gen. Charles Q. Brown Jr. said last week during a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tommy-tuberville-goes-on-defense-over-hold-on-military-promotions-racial-comments-235c8ed2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">confirmation hearing to become the next chairman</a> of the Joint Chiefs of Staff. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="756" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821178?width=1260&amp;height=756" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> As one potential option for its future cargo fleet, the US envisions a plane with a blended-wing body concept, similar to an Air Force prototype, shown in a 2006 rendering.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Illustration: Boeing</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> For now, the jumbo jet-sized C-5, which entered service in 1970 and the C-17, which joined the fleet in 1993, form the backbone of the transport fleet. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BA" class="company-name">Boeing</a> ended C-17 production in 2015, and the Air Force operates around 220 of them. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LMT" class="company-name">Lockheed Martin</a> stopped making the C-5 in 2002, and 52 remain in the fleet.</p><p> “Those planes aren&#39;t getting any younger because the C-17 was brand spankin&#39; new when I started flying in 1996,” said Darren McDew, a retired general who led the US Transportation Command.</p><p> The C-5 has doors at the front and the back to enable troops and supplies to be loaded and unloaded at the same time from cavernous cargo bays. Like the C-17, it has high wings and four powerful engines allowing them to operate from even small, unpaved runways. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1154" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/1195d348-3a5c-41cb-84c1-1e1b25063f9b-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> For the future, one option under consideration is an aircraft with a so-called <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-weird-looking-fuel-efficient-planes-you-could-be-flying-in-one-day-11667397440?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">blended-wing body concept</a> , essentially a flying wing that replaces the traditional tube-and-wings arrangement with a broad fuselage that also provides lift. The basic design isn&#39;t new, but advances in materials and production have brought the aircraft a step closer to reality.</p><p> A wing-body offers more interior space to carry supplies or fuel and, with new engines being designed, would provide the range to operate across the Pacific. The Air Force, National Aeronautics and Space Administration and the Pentagon&#39;s Defense Innovation Unit have teamed up to seek proposals for a full-scale demonstration version of such a design by 2027.</p><p> Lockheed and Boeing designed the C-5 and the C-17 to supply allied forces facing the threat of the former Soviet Union. Both can cross the Atlantic, make a stop and then fly another 500 miles without refueling. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818028?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A US Air Force C-17 Globemaster flew out of from Kabul in 2021 with 640 passengers aboard.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Us Air force/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> But for the last several years, the Pentagon has been <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pentagons-top-general-mark-milley-calls-for-faster-weapons-sales-to-taiwan-696f6504?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">focusing its planning on China</a> , which the US describes as its prime strategic competitor and the “pacing threat” it must match or surpass in military hardware and preparedness.</p><p> While a transport plane resupplying bases in Europe and the Middle East might fly hundreds of miles, the distances stretch to thousands in the Pacific. It is around 2,550 miles from Los Angeles to Hawaii. Guam, a hub for US forces in the region, is another 4,000 miles. In the event of a conflict, US aircraft would be vulnerable on the long flights.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Is the US military taking the right steps to modernize? Why, or why note?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> The new planes will need to be able to land at smaller airports, part of the Pentagon&#39;s plan to distribute forces and supplies of fuel and ammunition in the Pacific over a broad area rather than concentrating them in fewer bases vulnerable to Chinese attack.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-seeks-to-divert-ukrainian-forces-away-from-counteroffensive-80580e89?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">The conflict in Ukraine</a> is also informing requirements for the new planes, said Gen. Jacqueline Van Ovost, head of US Transportation Command, which oversees the Pentagon&#39;s air, sea and land logistics worldwide.</p><p> Van Ovost said the conflict in Ukraine made clear some of the needs for a new cargo plane that would, for example, allow Himars rocket launchers to be unloaded, fired and then flown to another site. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819259?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Air Force C-17 Globemaster entered service in 1993; the Air Force operates around 220 of the aircraft today.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: darek delmanowicz/EPA/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “It&#39;s clearly going to be a roll-on, roll-off,” said Van Ovost, a former test pilot who is widely tipped as a future chief of the Air Force, about the future cargo planes&#39; capabilities.</p><p> Anticipating the huge revenues to be won designing, building and maintaining new transport planes, the major defense contractors have been pushing a variety of designs for years.</p><p> Boeing said it has invested in technologies to support a blended-wing design and was assessing future concepts for airlift and tanker requirements. Lockheed Martin said it was ready to support the replacement of the airlift fleet and had invested in autonomous systems and communications, as well as aerodynamic efficiency.</p><p> Frank Kendall, the Air Force secretary, said a new airlift aircraft is unlikely to be a version of a commercial airliner, such as the Boeing 767 used as the basis for the KC-46A refueling tanker. Existing designs are easily visible on radar and lack defensive systems such as missiles to ensure they can complete missions. “It&#39;s a fairly wide open range of possibilities,” he said. “We may need a purpose-built aircraft and configuration which is much more survivable.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819266?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An Apache attack helicopter in 2017 emerged from the cargo bay of a Galaxy C-5 cargo plane.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: martin goldhahn/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> A clean-sheet design would increase the cost of replacement aircraft. The Air Force is spending around $40 billion on its new fleet of refueling tankers but has yet to provide any estimates for new cargo planes.</p><p> The opportunities aren&#39;t lost on big aircraft makers, who continue to offer the Air Force alternatives, even as its priorities shift to the Pacific.</p><p> “You name a person who builds an airplane, they pitch,” McDew said.</p><p> Write to Doug Cameron at <a href="mailto:Doug.Cameron@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Doug.Cameron@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 17:39:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/united-states-air-force-cargo-plane-development-china-1075021a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/united-states-air-force-cargo-plane-development-china-1075021a<author><![CDATA[Doug Cameron]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>空军</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> air force</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Threads User Engagement Continues to Decline]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Data show user engagement has fallen 70% as executives focus on options such as a chronological feed <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001072109"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821286?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Meta executives have signaled that they don&#39;t see the falloff as worrisome and have said they are working on additional features.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Etienne Laurent/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001072109"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/lindsey-choo" itemprop="url" rel="author">Lindsey Choo</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 21, 2023 10:48 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/threads-user-engagement-continues-to-drop-adding-urgency-for-new-features-8ed2f384"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> User engagement on Threads has continued to fall after an initial surge in sign-ups, putting pressure on parent <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Meta Platforms</a> to roll out new features for its <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/threads-twitter-new-features-eaac8c36?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">nascent microblogging app</a> .</p><p> For a second week in a row, the number of daily active users declined on Threads, falling to 13 million, down about 70% from a July 7 peak, according to estimates from market intelligence firm Sensor Tower.</p><p> The average time users spend on the iOS and Android apps has also decreased to four minutes from 19 minutes. The average time spent for Android users in the US dropped to five minutes from a peak of 21 minutes <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/early-success-of-metas-threads-is-already-drawing-interest-from-advertisers-ba67d722?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">on launch day</a> , according to SimilarWeb, a digital data and analytics company.</p><p> Twitter&#39;s daily active users remain steady at about 200 million, and average time spent is at 30 minutes a day, according to Sensor Tower estimates.</p><p> Meta executives have said they expected an eventual decline after the app gained more than <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-rapid-rise-of-threads-appears-to-be-hurting-twitter-f557ba6e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">100 million sign-ups</a> within a week of its launching earlier this month. They have signaled that they don&#39;t see the falloff as worrisome and have said they are <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/metas-threads-now-has-to-keep-its-millions-of-users-engaged-343e345b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">working on additional features</a> . Meta aims to increase the number of users and improve the experience before trying to monetize the platform. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="670" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821358?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “It&#39;s clear by the drop-off that people are seeing they can&#39;t do as much, and there are certain things that they want to be able to do that perhaps they can do on other apps,” said Richard Hanna, a professor at Babson College who studies social-media strategy and digital marketing. There is a need to increase what the app can do, he said.</p><p> Some writers and reviewers have said that Threads, which was built <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/zuckerberg-channeled-og-mark-to-fast-track-secret-effort-that-became-threads-86ce532e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">using Instagram&#39;s infrastructure</a> , might seem dull to certain users if they choose to follow the same people they follow on Instagram, since some of those accounts may not be posting nearly as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/threads-app-twitter-features-differences-dc943cd2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">frequently as they do on Twitter</a> . Company brands have been prevalent so far on Threads, an issue that some users have complained about on the platform.</p><p> The official Threads account on Thursday reiterated the company&#39;s plans to add new features. It reposted a video of Adam Mosseri —the head of Meta&#39;s Instagram unit, which produced Threads—from about a week ago in which he promised a laundry list of new features.</p><p> “ICYMI: we&#39;re working on getting you those new features,” the Threads post said. Among the features promised by Mosseri are support for multiple accounts, the ability to edit posts and a chronological feed option like the ones on Instagram and Facebook.</p><p> A Meta spokeswoman declined to comment. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821532?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;ICYMI: we&#39;re working on getting you those new features,&#39; Adam Mosseri, head of Meta&#39;s Instagram unit, said in a recent Threads post.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：迈克尔·布罗克斯坦/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>While it is still early days for the app, it has already made initial efforts to differentiate itself from Twitter, positioning itself as a platform with a different ethos that doesn&#39;t encourage politics or hard news.</p><p> Threads has more time to succeed than other startups because it can continue to invest in the app&#39;s success while it adds features and fixes any issues, analysts said. “Meta definitely has the patience, they have the money, and they have the engineering talent,” said Debra Aho Williamson, principal analyst at Insider Intelligence, a market research firm.</p><p> While the company has unveiled new features, some were recently delayed because of technical issues.</p><p> Cameron Roth, a software engineer at Instagram, posted to Threads on Tuesday that the iOS version of the app dropped an update that had many new features—which included translation, a follows tab on the activity feed, and a new subscription feature for unfollowed users.</p><p> However, Roth said on Wednesday in a separate post that the update rollout was paused while the company investigates an issue causing networking requests to fail.</p><p> Leaders at Meta have stressed that while the response in user engagement in the initial launch has exceeded expectations, they are giving priority to stabilization before engagement.</p><p> Mosseri said in a post on Threads last week that the “focus right now is not engagement, which has been amazing, but getting past the initial peak and trough we see with every new product, and building new features, dialing in performance, and improving ranking.”</p><p> Meta Chief Executive</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mark-zuckerberg">Mark Zuckerberg</a> echoed the sentiments in a post on Threads <strong>&nbsp;</strong> Monday. The company is focused on stabilizing before focusing on growing the community, he said.<p></p><p> Write to Lindsey Choo at <a href="mailto:lindsey.choo@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">lindsey.choo@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 14:48:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/threads-user-engagement-continues-to-drop-adding-urgency-for-new-features-8ed2f384</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/threads-user-engagement-continues-to-drop-adding-urgency-for-new-features-8ed2f384<author><![CDATA[Lindsey Choo]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>Software</category><category> Applications Software</category><category>计算</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>Mobile Applications Software</category><category> Social Media Platforms/Tools</category><category>技术</category><category>新产品/服务</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>产品与服务</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>Social Media</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>元平台</category><category>梅塔</category><category>新产品</category><category>服务</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>产品</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>social media</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>电脑</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>software</category><category> applications software</category><category> computing</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category><category>mobile applications software</category><category> social media platforms</category><category> tools</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Sergey Brin Is Back in the Trenches at Google]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>联合创始人正在与科技巨头总部的人工智能研究人员一起工作，协助建立强大的 Gemini 系统<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071343"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="577" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821144?width=860&amp;height=577" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">谷歌联合创始人谢尔盖·布林长期以来对人工智能技术很感兴趣，他定期与参与人工智能研究的谷歌员工会面。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：JUNG YEON-JE/​​法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071343"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/miles-kruppa" itemprop="url" rel="author">迈尔斯·克鲁帕</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/deepa-seetharaman" itemprop="url" rel="author">迪帕·西塔拉曼</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 21 日上午 10:10（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sergey-brin-google-ai-gemini-1b5aa41e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>谷歌联合创始人谢尔盖·布林重返工作岗位。</p><p>近几个月来，这位亿万富翁每周都会访问这家科技巨头位于加州山景城的办公室，通常每周三到四天，与研究人员一起努力开发该公司的下一个大型人工智能系统。</p><p>知情人士称，布林去年年底参加了谷歌办公室有关人工智能的会议，但他参与的频率和强度有所增加。他的新立场与他在 2019 年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sundar-pichai-to-replace-larry-page-as-ceo-of-alphabet-11575409229?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">辞去</a>母公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GOOG" class="company-name">Alphabet</a>高管职务后采取的相对不干涉的态度发生了显着变化。</p><p>他与一组研究人员密切合作，构建了谷歌期待已久的人工智能模型 Gemini。他们讨论了诸如“损失曲线”之类的技术问题，这是一种衡量人工智能程序随时间推移表现的方法，布林还每周与谷歌员工就新的人工智能研究进行讨论。知情人士称，他还干预人事事务，例如聘用受欢迎的研究人员。</p><p>现任和前任员工表示，布林在谷歌的影响力增加反映了人工智能的关键时刻以及他对这项技术的长期兴趣。谷歌是该技术的先驱，但在将其转化为新产品方面比竞争对手慢。</p><p>随着 Meta Platforms 等公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-and-microsoft-team-up-to-distribute-new-ai-software-for-commercial-use-c4f7b634?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">最近推出的新产品</a>，人工智能研究领域的竞争正在加剧。谷歌<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-tries-to-catch-up-to-rivals-like-openai-as-they-release-viral-apps-11674828418?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">加快了产品开发速度，</a>以应对去年发布的 ChatGPT，这是一款由<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">微软</a>支持的研究公司 OpenAI 开发的人工智能聊天机器人，可以流畅地响应一系列书面查询。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820793?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">谷歌创始人谢尔盖·布林和拉里·佩奇从斯坦福大学博士生起就一直在一起工作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：迈克尔·内格尔/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Gemini 是 Google 尝试构建的<a href="https://blog.google/technology/ai/google-palm-2-ai-large-language-model/" target="_blank" class="icon none">通用人工智能</a>程序，可以与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/openai-rolls-out-updated-version-of-viral-chatbot-chatgpt-f03fea27?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">OpenAI 的 GPT-4 模型</a>相媲美，该模型为 ChatGPT 的付费版本提供支持。据知情人士透露，负责该项目的谷歌高管德米斯·哈萨比斯 (Demis Hassabis) 在最近的一次全公司会议上告诉员工，该项目将于今年晚些时候推出。</p><p> 49 岁的布林于 1998 年与拉里·佩奇 (Larry Page) 一起创立了谷歌，他们在斯坦福大学攻读博士时共同进行了网络搜索研究。</p><p>虽然布林近年来偶尔出现在谷歌总部，但他的注意力主要集中在飞艇和新形式的灾难援助等外部利益上，以及捐赠部分巨额财富的努力。根据 S&amp;P Capital IQ 的数据，他是 Alphabet 的第二大个人股东，仅次于 Page，所持股份价值接近 900 亿美元。</p><p>自从谷歌在 5 月份的年度开发者大会上宣布一系列人工智能产品以来，Alphabet 的股价已经上涨了 10% 以上，其中包括新版本的核心搜索引擎，该引擎提供了冗长的摘要并邀请后续问题。这一涨幅与竞争对手微软的股价和更广泛的纳斯达克综合指数大致一致。</p><p>知情人士称，布林大部分时间都在新建的查尔斯顿东大楼里与山景城的人工智能研究人员坐在一起，该大楼距离谷歌公司园区原来的中心仅几步之遥。谷歌和 Alphabet 的首席执行官桑达尔·皮查伊 (Sundar Pichai) 也在大楼内设有办公室。</p><p>四年前，当创始人辞去日常职务并将皮查伊提拔为 Alphabet 首席执行官时，他们表示将定期与他交谈并提供“建议和爱，但不会每天唠叨”。他们仍然控制着 Alphabet 的多数投票权，并与皮查伊一起担任执行董事会委员会成员。</p><p>据一位了解皮查伊想法的人士透露，皮查伊对布林的参与感到兴奋，并鼓励他做出贡献。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="475" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820792?width=700&amp;height=475" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2012 年，谢尔盖·布林 (Sergey Brin) 与一辆自动驾驶汽车在谷歌山景城总部。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：贾斯汀·沙利文/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>谷歌在人工智能领域处于领先地位，于 2011 年成立了一个名为 Brain 的研究部门，研究如何使用称为深度学习的计算技术来构建广泛有用的人工智能程序。</p><p> Pichai 今年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/alphabets-google-combines-ai-research-units-brain-and-deepmind-620f4f7d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将 Brain 团队与 DeepMind 合并</a>，DeepMind 是一家人工智能研究公司，此前在 Alphabet 旗下独立运营。这次改组将 DeepMind 联合创始人哈萨比斯提升为合并后的 Google DeepMind 集团的首席执行官。</p><p>现任和前任员工表示，一些研究人员接受了布林的参与，认为这是对他们工作的认可，也是人工智能团队在过渡时期的有益干预。哈萨比斯和许多 Google DeepMind 高管在伦敦工作，使该办公室成为新设置中事实上的权力中心。</p><p>自 11 月份 ChatGPT 发布以来，布林的参与度不断增加。据《纽约时报》早些时候报道的知情人士透露，谷歌的联合创始人参加了会议，审查谷歌正在为 5 月份的开发者大会准备的人工智能产品。</p><p>此后，布林一直在谷歌总部保持着强大的影响力，经常出席研究聚会和公司庆祝活动。谷歌表示，除了联合创始人和董事会成员之外，布林在公司没有正式的新角色。布林的发言人没有回应置评请求。</p><p>佩奇在管理谷歌期间有时是一个隐居的人物，而布林却培养了一个更平易近人的形象，穿着溜冰鞋穿越总部，在公司的各个项目之间穿梭。</p><p>据与布林有过互动的人士透露，自从去年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-in-talks-to-invest-200-million-into-ai-startup-11666381180?&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">人工智能热潮</a>以来，布林就参加了该公司的发布会，该公司推广了图像生成程序 Stable Diffusion，并且偶尔也会参加在加利福尼亚州希尔斯伯勒一座价值 6800 万美元的豪宅（即 AGI House）举行的活动。 AGI 代表通用人工智能，即计算机程序有一天可以与人类推理相匹配。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="507" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820384?width=700&amp;height=507" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">今年早些时候，谷歌首席执行官桑达尔·皮查伊、谢尔盖·布林、卢森堡首相泽维尔·贝特尔和谷歌全球事务总裁肯特·沃克。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：卢森堡国务部</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>今年3月，在<a href="https://www.linkedin.com/posts/xavier-bettel_thanks-to-sundar-pichai-and-kent-walker-activity-7041634974231351296-hDnQ/" target="_blank" class="icon none">卢森堡首相访问期间，布林被拍到与皮查伊和谷歌全球事务总裁肯特·沃克在谷歌总部合影</a>，布林身着灰色运动裤和黑色长袖衬衫。其他与会者都穿着西装。</p><p>布林与 Gemini 的合作是谷歌长期努力构建人工智能系统的又一成果，这些系统可以展现出类人的能力，并更无缝地满足该公司数十亿用户的需求。</p><p>布林在 2017 年 <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ffvu6Mr1SVc&amp;t=92s" target="_blank" class="icon none">世界经济论坛上接受采访</a>时表示，起初，布林忽视了 Brain 团队的工作，并对他们能否破解人工智能表示怀疑，尽管该团队始于他领导的 Google X 部门。</p><p> “说实话，我根本没有注意它，”布林说。他说，几年后，Brain 的研究被用于谷歌许多最大的产品，颠覆了他之前的假设。</p><p>布林在一定程度上关注了人事问题，随着人工智能研究人员的人才争夺战加剧，这对谷歌和其他大型科技公司来说是一个困难的领域。 2017 年，谷歌发表了一篇具有里程碑意义的论文，该论文被认为引发了最新一波人工智能发展浪潮，该论文的多位作者已离开该公司，为竞争对手的初创公司筹集数亿美元资金。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>谢尔盖·布林会让谷歌在人工智能领域更具竞争力吗？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>现任和前任员工表示，尽管布林是世界上最受尊敬的计算机科学家之一，但他需要赶上人工智能的最新发展，并且没有为编码项目做出重大贡献。</p><p>布林在 2018 年发布的上一封股东信中宣传了人工智能的可能性，他写道，“计算解决重要问题的力量和潜力从未如此强大。”</p><p> “人工智能的新春天是我一生中计算领域最重大的发展，”他写道。</p><p>写信给 Miles Kruppa ( <a href="mailto:miles.kruppa@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">miles.kruppa@wsj.com)</a>和 Deepa Seetharaman ( <a href="mailto:deepa.seetharaman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">deepa.seetharaman@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 14:10:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/sergey-brin-google-ai-gemini-1b5aa41e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/sergey-brin-google-ai-gemini-1b5aa41e<author><![CDATA[Miles KruppaDeepa Seetharaman]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>专有的</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>市场研究/公共关系</category><category>公共关系</category><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>广告/营销/公共关系</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category><category>新产品/服务</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>产品与服务</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>高净值个人</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>字母</category><category>谷歌</category><category>元平台</category><category>梅塔</category><category>谢尔盖·布林</category><category>新产品</category><category>服务</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>产品</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>高净值个人</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业