          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="577" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821144?width=860&amp;height=577" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">谷歌联合创始人谢尔盖·布林长期以来对人工智能技术很感兴趣，他定期与参与人工智能研究的谷歌员工会面。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：JUNG YEON-JE/​​法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071343"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/miles-kruppa" itemprop="url" rel="author">迈尔斯·克鲁帕</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/deepa-seetharaman" itemprop="url" rel="author">迪帕·西塔拉曼</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 21 日上午 10:10（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sergey-brin-google-ai-gemini-1b5aa41e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>谷歌联合创始人谢尔盖·布林重返工作岗位。</p><p>近几个月来，这位亿万富翁每周都会访问这家科技巨头位于加州山景城的办公室，通常每周三到四天，与研究人员一起努力开发该公司的下一个大型人工智能系统。</p><p>知情人士称，布林去年年底参加了谷歌办公室有关人工智能的会议，但他参与的频率和强度有所增加。他的新立场与他在 2019 年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sundar-pichai-to-replace-larry-page-as-ceo-of-alphabet-11575409229?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">辞去</a>母公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GOOG" class="company-name">Alphabet</a>高管职务后采取的相对不干涉的态度发生了显着变化。</p><p>他与一组研究人员密切合作，构建了谷歌期待已久的人工智能模型 Gemini。他们讨论了诸如“损失曲线”之类的技术问题，这是一种衡量人工智能程序随时间推移表现的方法，布林还每周与谷歌员工就新的人工智能研究进行讨论。知情人士称，他还干预人事事务，例如聘用受欢迎的研究人员。</p><p>现任和前任员工表示，布林在谷歌的影响力增加反映了人工智能的关键时刻以及他对这项技术的长期兴趣。谷歌是该技术的先驱，但在将其转化为新产品方面比竞争对手慢。</p><p>随着 Meta Platforms 等公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-and-microsoft-team-up-to-distribute-new-ai-software-for-commercial-use-c4f7b634?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">最近推出的新产品</a>，人工智能研究领域的竞争正在加剧。谷歌<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-tries-to-catch-up-to-rivals-like-openai-as-they-release-viral-apps-11674828418?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">加快了产品开发速度，</a>以应对去年发布的 ChatGPT，这是一款由<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">微软</a>支持的研究公司 OpenAI 开发的人工智能聊天机器人，可以流畅地响应一系列书面查询。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820793?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">谷歌创始人谢尔盖·布林和拉里·佩奇从斯坦福大学博士生起就一直在一起工作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：迈克尔·内格尔/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Gemini 是 Google 尝试构建的<a href="https://blog.google/technology/ai/google-palm-2-ai-large-language-model/" target="_blank" class="icon none">通用人工智能</a>程序，可以与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/openai-rolls-out-updated-version-of-viral-chatbot-chatgpt-f03fea27?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">OpenAI 的 GPT-4 模型</a>相媲美，该模型为 ChatGPT 的付费版本提供支持。据知情人士透露，负责该项目的谷歌高管德米斯·哈萨比斯 (Demis Hassabis) 在最近的一次全公司会议上告诉员工，该项目将于今年晚些时候推出。</p><p> 49 岁的布林于 1998 年与拉里·佩奇 (Larry Page) 一起创立了谷歌，他们在斯坦福大学攻读博士时共同进行了网络搜索研究。</p><p>虽然布林近年来偶尔出现在谷歌总部，但他的注意力主要集中在飞艇和新形式的灾难援助等外部利益上，以及捐赠部分巨额财富的努力。根据 S&amp;P Capital IQ 的数据，他是 Alphabet 的第二大个人股东，仅次于 Page，所持股份价值接近 900 亿美元。</p><p>自从谷歌在 5 月份的年度开发者大会上宣布一系列人工智能产品以来，Alphabet 的股价已经上涨了 10% 以上，其中包括新版本的核心搜索引擎，该引擎提供了冗长的摘要并邀请后续问题。这一涨幅与竞争对手微软的股价和更广泛的纳斯达克综合指数大致一致。</p><p>知情人士称，布林大部分时间都在新建的查尔斯顿东大楼里与山景城的人工智能研究人员坐在一起，该大楼距离谷歌公司园区原来的中心仅几步之遥。谷歌和 Alphabet 的首席执行官桑达尔·皮查伊 (Sundar Pichai) 也在大楼内设有办公室。</p><p>四年前，当创始人辞去日常职务并将皮查伊提拔为 Alphabet 首席执行官时，他们表示将定期与他交谈并提供“建议和爱，但不会每天唠叨”。他们仍然控制着 Alphabet 的多数投票权，并与皮查伊一起担任执行董事会委员会成员。</p><p>据一位了解皮查伊想法的人士透露，皮查伊对布林的参与感到兴奋，并鼓励他做出贡献。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="475" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820792?width=700&amp;height=475" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2012 年，谢尔盖·布林 (Sergey Brin) 与一辆自动驾驶汽车在谷歌山景城总部。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：贾斯汀·沙利文/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>谷歌在人工智能领域处于领先地位，于 2011 年成立了一个名为 Brain 的研究部门，研究如何使用称为深度学习的计算技术来构建广泛有用的人工智能程序。</p><p> Pichai 今年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/alphabets-google-combines-ai-research-units-brain-and-deepmind-620f4f7d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将 Brain 团队与 DeepMind 合并</a>，DeepMind 是一家人工智能研究公司，此前在 Alphabet 旗下独立运营。这次改组将 DeepMind 联合创始人哈萨比斯提升为合并后的 Google DeepMind 集团的首席执行官。</p><p>现任和前任员工表示，一些研究人员接受了布林的参与，认为这是对他们工作的认可，也是人工智能团队在过渡时期的有益干预。哈萨比斯和许多 Google DeepMind 高管在伦敦工作，使该办公室成为新设置中事实上的权力中心。</p><p>自 11 月份 ChatGPT 发布以来，布林的参与度不断增加。据《纽约时报》早些时候报道的知情人士透露，谷歌的联合创始人参加了会议，审查谷歌正在为 5 月份的开发者大会准备的人工智能产品。</p><p>此后，布林一直在谷歌总部保持着强大的影响力，经常出席研究聚会和公司庆祝活动。谷歌表示，除了联合创始人和董事会成员之外，布林在公司没有正式的新角色。布林的发言人没有回应置评请求。</p><p>佩奇在管理谷歌期间有时是一个隐居的人物，而布林却培养了一个更平易近人的形象，穿着溜冰鞋穿越总部，在公司的各个项目之间穿梭。</p><p>据与布林有过互动的人士透露，自从去年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-in-talks-to-invest-200-million-into-ai-startup-11666381180?&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">人工智能热潮</a>以来，布林就参加了该公司的发布会，该公司推广了图像生成程序 Stable Diffusion，并且偶尔也会参加在加利福尼亚州希尔斯伯勒一座价值 6800 万美元的豪宅（即 AGI House）举行的活动。 AGI 代表通用人工智能，即计算机程序有一天可以与人类推理相匹配。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="507" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820384?width=700&amp;height=507" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">今年早些时候，谷歌首席执行官桑达尔·皮查伊、谢尔盖·布林、卢森堡首相泽维尔·贝特尔和谷歌全球事务总裁肯特·沃克。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：卢森堡国务部</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>今年3月，在<a href="https://www.linkedin.com/posts/xavier-bettel_thanks-to-sundar-pichai-and-kent-walker-activity-7041634974231351296-hDnQ/" target="_blank" class="icon none">卢森堡首相访问期间，布林被拍到与皮查伊和谷歌全球事务总裁肯特·沃克在谷歌总部合影</a>，布林身着灰色运动裤和黑色长袖衬衫。其他与会者都穿着西装。</p><p>布林与 Gemini 的合作是谷歌长期努力构建人工智能系统的又一成果，这些系统可以展现出类人的能力，并更无缝地满足该公司数十亿用户的需求。</p><p>布林在 2017 年 <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ffvu6Mr1SVc&amp;t=92s" target="_blank" class="icon none">世界经济论坛上接受采访</a>时表示，起初，布林忽视了 Brain 团队的工作，并对他们能否破解人工智能表示怀疑，尽管该团队始于他领导的 Google X 部门。</p><p> “说实话，我根本没有注意它，”布林说。他说，几年后，Brain 的研究被用于谷歌许多最大的产品，颠覆了他之前的假设。</p><p>布林在一定程度上关注了人事问题，随着人工智能研究人员的人才争夺战加剧，这对谷歌和其他大型科技公司来说是一个困难的领域。 2017 年，谷歌发表了一篇具有里程碑意义的论文，该论文被认为引发了最新一波人工智能发展浪潮，该论文的多位作者已离开该公司，为竞争对手的初创公司筹集数亿美元资金。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>谢尔盖·布林会让谷歌在人工智能领域更具竞争力吗？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>现任和前任员工表示，尽管布林是世界上最受尊敬的计算机科学家之一，但他需要赶上人工智能的最新发展，并且没有为编码项目做出重大贡献。</p><p>布林在 2018 年发布的上一封股东信中宣传了人工智能的可能性，他写道，“计算解决重要问题的力量和潜力从未如此强大。”</p><p> “人工智能的新春天是我一生中计算领域最重大的发展，”他写道。</p><p>写信给 Miles Kruppa ( <a href="mailto:miles.kruppa@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">miles.kruppa@wsj.com)</a>和 Deepa Seetharaman ( <a href="mailto:deepa.seetharaman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">deepa.seetharaman@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 14:10:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/sergey-brin-google-ai-gemini-1b5aa41e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/sergey-brin-google-ai-gemini-1b5aa41e<author><![CDATA[Miles KruppaDeepa Seetharaman]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>专有的</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>市场研究/公共关系</category><category>公共关系</category><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>广告/营销/公共关系</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category><category>新产品/服务</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>产品与服务</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>高净值个人</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>字母</category><category>谷歌</category><category>元平台</category><category>梅塔</category><category>谢尔盖·布林</category><category>新产品</category><category>服务</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>产品</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>高净值个人</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>市场调查</category><category>公共关系</category><category>互联网搜索引擎</category><category>广告</category><category>营销</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Rise and Fall of the Chief Diversity Officer]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Diversity executives hit the exits as company priorities shift; &#39;everything is a battle&#39; <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071159"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820139?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> From left: Melinda Starbird, a human resources and diversity executive; Dani Monroe, former CDO for Mass General Brigham; and Miriam Warren, CDO for Yelp.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo Illustration: Melinda Starbird, Cheryl Richard, Yelp </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071159"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/te-ping-chen" itemprop="url" rel="author">Te-Ping Chen</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/lauren-weber" itemprop="url" rel="author">Lauren Weber</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 21, 2023 7:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chief-diversity-officer-cdo-business-corporations-e110a82f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Two years ago chief diversity officers were some of the hottest hires into executive ranks. Now, they increasingly feel left out in the cold.</p><p> Companies including <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NFLX" class="">Netflix</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/DIS" class="company-name">Disney</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WBD" class="company-name">Warner Bros. Discovery</a> have recently said that high-profile diversity, equity and inclusion executives will be leaving their jobs. Thousands of diversity-focused workers have been laid off since last year, and some companies are <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/diversity-workplace-affirmative-action-dei-3646683b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">scaling back</a> racial justice commitments.</p><p> Diversity, equity and inclusion—or DEI—jobs were put in the crosshairs after many companies started re-examining their executive ranks during the tech sector&#39;s shake out last fall. Some chief diversity officers say their work is facing additional scrutiny since the Supreme Court <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-rules-against-affirmative-action-c94b5a9c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">struck down affirmative action</a> in college admissions and companies brace for <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/republican-attorneys-general-warn-top-u-s-businesses-over-discrimination-1eb78d29?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">potential legal challenges</a> . DEI work has also become a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ron-desantiss-education-policies-leave-florida-teachers-feeling-unsure-3a81a236?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">political target</a> .</p><p> “There&#39;s a combination of grief, being very tired, and being, in some cases, overwhelmed,” says Miriam Warren, chief diversity officer for <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/YELP" class="">Yelp</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> of the challenges facing executives in the field.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> In interviews, current and former chief diversity officers said company executives at times didn&#39;t want to change hiring or promotion processes, despite initially telling CDOs they were hired to improve the talent pipeline. The quick about-face shows company enthusiasm for diversity initiatives hasn&#39;t always proved durable, leaving some diversity officers now questioning their career path.</p><p> In the wake of George Floyd&#39;s murder in police custody in May 2020, companies scrambled to hire chief diversity officers, changing the face of the C-suite. In 2018, less than half the companies in the S&amp;P 500 employed someone in the role, and by 2022 three out four companies had created a position, according to a study from Russell Reynolds, an executive search firm.</p><p> Once mostly tasked with HR matters, today&#39;s diversity leaders are expected to weigh in on new product development, marketing efforts and current events that have an impact on how workers and consumers are feeling. Warren and other CDOs said the expanded remit is playing out in a politically divided environment where corporate diversity efforts are the subject of frequent <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/companies-new-cause-dodging-the-culture-wars-73e52cf3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">social-media firestorms</a> .</p><h3> Falling demand</h3><p> New analysis from employment data provider Live Data Technologies shows that chief diversity officers have been more vulnerable to layoffs than their human resources counterparts, experiencing 40% higher turnover. Their job searches are also taking longer.</p><p> “I got to 300 applications and then I stopped tracking,” says Stephanie Lubin, who was laid off from her role as diversity head at Drizly, an online alcohol marketplace, in May following the company&#39;s acquisition by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UBER" class="">Uber</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span></p> In one case, Lubin says she went through 16 rounds of interviews for a role she didn&#39;t get, and says she is now planning to pivot out of DEI work.<p></p><p> The number of CDO searches is down 75% in the past year, says Jason Hanold, chief executive of Hanold Associates Executive Search, which works with Fortune 100 companies to recruit HR and DEI executives, among other roles. Demand is the lowest he has seen in his 30 years of recruiting.</p><p> At the same time, he says, more executives are feeling skittish about taking on diversity roles.</p><p> “They&#39;re telling us, the only way I want to go into another role with DEI is if it includes something else,” he says of the requests for broader titles that offer more responsibilities and resources. He estimates that 60% of diversity roles he is currently filling combine the title with another position, such as chief human resources officer, up from about 10% five years ago.</p><p> During the pandemic, some companies moved people into diversity leadership if they were an ethnic minority, says</p> Dani Monroe, even when they weren&#39;t qualified. Monroe served as CDO for Mass General Brigham, a Boston-based hospital system and one of the largest employers in the state, until 2021 and convenes a yearly gathering of more than 100 CDOs.<p></p><p> “These were knee-jerk reactions,” she says of the hurried CDO hires, adding that some of those elevations didn&#39;t create much impact, leaving both sides feeling disillusioned.</p><h3> On-the-job obstruction</h3><p> American workers are split on the importance of a diverse workforce, <a href="https://www.pewresearch.org/social-trends/2023/05/17/diversity-equity-and-inclusion-in-the-workplace/" target="_blank" class="icon none">surveys find</a> .</p><p> Diversity chiefs also encounter obstruction from top executives, says Melinda Starbird, a human resources and diversity executive who has worked at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/T" class="">AT&amp;T</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span></p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SBUX" class="company-name">Starbucks</a> and OfferUp, an online marketplace. Leaders sometimes associate diversity efforts with mandates, such as the equal-employment rules that apply to federal contractors. Those requirements for compliance can create executive resistance that bleeds over into other cultural or policy shifts, such as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-to-sign-bill-making-juneteenth-a-federal-holiday-11623944038?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">adding Juneteenth</a> as a company holiday, she says.<p></p><p> “Even if you report to the CEO, it&#39;s still a battle and it&#39;s a smaller budget,” says Starbird, who was laid off from OfferUp in November during a broader restructuring.</p><p> Many diversity executives feel a lack of buy-in from their colleagues. In <a href="https://urldefense.com/v3/__https://world50.com/impact?utm_source=wsj&amp;utm_medium=pr&amp;utm_campaign=2023idreport__;!!F0Stn7g!EGLdSj-lMiFGnMwE-GKlWcgVj1tXMu0_-ZbTIyBUUYuQV0JylSZhtrfPiJ-A4c5JWSBx3Po2kxjQHsQPCw$" target="_blank" class="icon none">a survey</a> of 138 diversity executives conducted this spring by World 50 Group, a networking organization for corporate leaders, 82% said they had sufficient influence to do their job, down 6 percentage points from 2022. Asked if they felt supported by middle managers, 41% said yes, an 8-percentage-point drop.</p><p> Since the Supreme Court overturned affirmative action in June, companies are anticipating spillover legal action could have an impact on them. Those that are still hiring CDOs want people who can help the board navigate the political and legal landscape of diversity work and figure out how to take defensive moves to shield them from litigation, says Tina Shah Paikeday, global leader of Russell Reynolds&#39;s diversity, equity and inclusion practice.</p><p> “They recognize it would be smart to get ahead of that.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820155?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> David Kenny, chief executive of Nielsen, says efforts to restructure compensation to make it more equitable created a backlash.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Nielsen</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> People are more resistant to company-backed efforts to advance diversity when they are worried about their own jobs, whether because of impending layoffs or disruptions from AI, says David Kenny, chief executive of Nielsen, the media-ratings company.</p><p> Kenny was both CEO and CDO for a time, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chief-executive-or-diversity-chief-nielsens-ceo-is-both-11608908446?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">taking on</a> the diversity role to emphasize how important it was to the future of the business. Even as CEO, it could be a tough sell. Efforts to restructure compensation to make it more equitable created a backlash.</p><p> “A lot of it is, &#39;I&#39;m losing my slice of the pie,&#39; ” he says. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
